Did it ever cut?

13:26.146 --> 13:30.613
Did you ever almost say cut, you know, when you saw this thing?

13:30.713 --> 13:35.421
I love two cocky socks up to here.

13:35.441 --> 13:36.723
What did you ask?

13:36.743 --> 13:40.429
We're not a wrinkle in them either.

13:40.449 --> 13:41.070
What did you say?

13:41.438 --> 13:41.879
I don't know.

13:41.939 --> 13:43.360
I'm trying to cut you off.

13:43.380 --> 13:45.243
I don't think it was that important.

13:46.464 --> 13:47.425
We've got that.

13:48.487 --> 13:49.268
We've got that.

13:49.408 --> 13:51.731
We've got just about everything here, you know.

13:51.751 --> 13:52.912
The theater of action.

13:53.293 --> 13:54.474
Strike away.

13:54.514 --> 13:57.758
What a pompous thing to call anything, the theater of action.

13:57.778 --> 13:58.759
Those were the days, Nick.

14:00.161 --> 14:00.762
Those were the days.

14:00.922 --> 14:02.604
And those kids didn't have a quarter.

14:03.806 --> 14:08.171
Do you remember the story in the book where they got paid with 20 pumpkin pies?

14:08.291 --> 14:08.431
Jesus.

14:08.512 --> 14:09.413
Eat anything.

14:09.433 --> 14:10.534
Apples.

14:12.016 --> 14:14.539
Vegetables, half shot, anything.

14:14.559 --> 14:15.640
I mean, they were so devoted.

14:15.660 --> 14:17.663
They lived together, they worked together every day.

14:18.343 --> 14:19.064
I couldn't take it.

14:19.465 --> 14:20.506
I don't like group living.

14:20.526 --> 14:23.630
I don't like, what do you call these things that Jews set up in there in Israel?

14:23.690 --> 14:24.070
Kibbutz.

14:24.190 --> 14:24.631
I hate them.

14:24.931 --> 14:26.773
I went to one, stayed there a week, drove me nuts.

14:27.975 --> 14:30.818
Remember the hippies back in the 60s called them demons?

14:32.019 --> 14:33.281
I don't like the hippies either.

14:33.621 --> 14:35.464
I don't like group this, that, the other.

14:35.484 --> 14:36.785
I was in the group theater, I didn't like it.

14:38.467 --> 14:41.871
I like being by myself, except when I want to be with somebody.

14:42.745 --> 14:45.549
And as an artist, do you think that that produces your best work?

14:45.569 --> 14:46.270
It's the whole thing.

14:47.632 --> 14:50.036
There's no such thing, I think, as art by committee anyway.

14:51.078 --> 14:53.261
The King James Bible, that's about it.

14:53.281 --> 14:58.769
That's kind of a question, actually.

14:59.230 --> 15:06.441
Play can be a product of a group activity, but there has to be a very strong leader, or else they go wild.

15:08.965 --> 15:09.265
Okay.

15:09.906 --> 15:11.689
You know what, I'm going to wrap this up pretty soon.

15:12.597 --> 15:14.720
Are you threatening me a promise?

15:14.760 --> 15:17.204
No, because I don't want to.

15:17.224 --> 15:20.249
I love the fact that you put aside money in your will for a great party.

15:21.151 --> 15:22.433
It's going to be a celebration.

15:23.795 --> 15:26.018
You don't want weeping, mourning people.

15:26.038 --> 15:28.262
I don't want anybody weeping over me, because why weep over me?

15:28.282 --> 15:29.023
I had a great life.

15:30.526 --> 15:37.877
I mean, if it stopped five minutes after you got here, if I fall on the floor, no, no, nothing.

15:37.897 --> 15:38.598
I had a great life.

15:38.618 --> 15:39.239
Don't you think so?

15:39.500 --> 15:39.600
Okay.

15:39.800 --> 15:40.721
Look at the life I had.

15:41.021 --> 15:41.742
Look at it.

15:42.943 --> 15:43.364
Everything.

15:43.484 --> 15:44.685
Everything.

15:44.705 --> 15:46.847
I had it all, including pain.

15:47.988 --> 15:48.989
I think pain is very good.

15:49.009 --> 15:49.870
It's very stimulating.

15:49.970 --> 15:50.871
It's important, isn't it?

15:51.552 --> 16:01.162
Well, anyway, I had a great life, so I don't want any moaning and groaning, and they can come and take my sweaters away and my books and everything they want.

16:01.182 --> 16:06.046
The only way you have catharsis in Greek pain at play is through terror and pity.

16:06.066 --> 16:07.248
I mean, there has to be pain.

16:07.268 --> 16:08.709
You have to suffer before you can have it.

16:08.749 --> 16:09.570
I don't want any pity.

16:11.305 --> 16:12.146
I don't want any terror.

16:12.186 --> 16:12.887
I had all that.

16:12.907 --> 16:13.648
I don't want terror.

16:13.668 --> 16:14.448
I don't want pity.

16:14.468 --> 16:17.372
I don't want catharsis.

16:17.392 --> 16:21.536
You do say that the only plays that you can relate to are contemporary plays.

16:21.556 --> 16:21.756
It's true.

16:22.998 --> 16:23.418
I have some.

16:23.438 --> 16:24.439
You've got the New York Times.

16:24.459 --> 16:25.280
I read that every day.

16:25.581 --> 16:26.121
It's a pleasure.

16:26.702 --> 16:27.623
I get something out of it.

16:28.123 --> 16:29.405
I read the news, too.

16:30.005 --> 16:30.866
I follow sports.

16:31.087 --> 16:32.388
I follow people.

16:32.428 --> 16:33.309
I follow gossip.

16:33.409 --> 16:34.450
I think it's all important.

16:36.372 --> 16:36.933
More years.

16:37.373 --> 16:38.334
Give me three wishes.

16:38.355 --> 16:38.815
That's the end.

16:39.014 --> 16:40.375
Not three, did you say three?

16:40.395 --> 16:41.296
No, you said three wishes.

16:41.336 --> 16:42.798
Oh, yeah, three wishes, yeah.

16:42.958 --> 16:44.499
I said wishes, I quoted you.

16:44.539 --> 16:46.722
Three shit, that's not it.

16:46.742 --> 16:49.104
Three shit, that's right.

16:49.124 --> 16:50.065
I want twenty more years.

16:50.886 --> 16:53.628
I'm seventy-eight and a half now, I'm seventy-ninth year.

16:54.149 --> 16:55.630
I want to go to just under a hundred.

16:56.571 --> 16:59.134
My father's the same, he's seventy-seven.

16:59.274 --> 17:01.696
He looks wonderful, a little fat, he loves to eat.

17:01.736 --> 17:04.799
But other than that, he's just a good man.

17:04.819 --> 17:05.840
I try not to eat too much.

17:05.880 --> 17:07.502
I shouldn't have eaten those goddamn cakes.

17:08.562 --> 17:09.183
You work out?

17:10.124 --> 17:12.186
No, I work in the garden.

17:12.307 --> 17:14.049
I hate walking out, but I walk every day.

17:14.109 --> 17:18.073
I walk two miles or three miles and try to walk fast.

17:19.075 --> 17:19.976
And I am in good shape.

17:20.596 --> 17:22.339
I'm not overweight.

17:22.359 --> 17:23.700
I wish I could say that.

17:23.720 --> 17:25.042
You've got a little belly.

17:25.222 --> 17:27.164
It's as big as it's ever been.

17:27.184 --> 17:28.346
You know, I've seen bigger bellies.

17:28.406 --> 17:31.289
Well, I mean, with me, it's as big as it's ever been.

17:31.349 --> 17:32.451
Oh, as big as it's ever been.

17:32.511 --> 17:33.272
What's your wife say?

17:33.292 --> 17:34.053
Doesn't she get married?

17:34.253 --> 17:35.194
Yeah, oh yeah.

17:35.967 --> 17:37.208
She's right.

17:37.228 --> 17:37.929
You shouldn't have it.

17:38.229 --> 17:39.130
What are you, 45?

17:39.170 --> 17:39.691
Something like that.

17:39.711 --> 17:40.251
Precisely.

17:40.572 --> 17:42.033
I'll be 45 next week.

17:42.073 --> 17:43.114
You shouldn't have it.

17:43.134 --> 17:45.096
You should start to take off weight now.

17:45.116 --> 17:47.398
When you're 55, you should be 10 pounds lighter.

17:47.418 --> 17:48.039
That's not much.

17:48.079 --> 17:48.139
No.

17:49.060 --> 17:50.181
I can do it, too.

17:50.201 --> 17:51.663
And I do work out.

17:51.723 --> 17:53.605
It's boring.

17:53.685 --> 17:55.206
I hate gyms.

17:55.226 --> 17:56.888
I don't like the smell of the gym locker room.

17:58.549 --> 18:00.912
Discipline is everything.

18:00.932 --> 18:02.093
What else can I ask you?

18:02.343 --> 18:06.568
Here's one, here's one good one I'm going to ask.

18:07.929 --> 18:14.597
Because I really resent the assertion, and you seem to have agreed with it, that you are an extinct volcano.

18:14.637 --> 18:19.462
That's an English critic.

18:19.502 --> 18:20.664
I didn't say it.

18:20.944 --> 18:23.226
An American critic didn't say it.

18:23.407 --> 18:24.908
I've been panned by some critics, you know.

18:25.109 --> 18:25.569
I'm sure.

18:25.629 --> 18:28.853
There's a guy up in Boston who just panned me today.

18:28.873 --> 18:29.974
I just got to know this today.

18:29.994 --> 18:30.915
He wrote in The Globe.

18:31.604 --> 18:33.827
And he said all my anecdotes were fake.

18:34.968 --> 18:35.829
Really?

18:35.849 --> 18:38.973
How does he propose to prove that?

18:39.774 --> 18:42.037
There's not a fake anecdote in the book.

18:42.057 --> 18:43.118
Who's the guy that wrote this?

18:43.379 --> 18:44.861
That Kevin Kelly.

18:44.881 --> 18:46.182
I don't know who he is.

18:46.202 --> 18:46.883
I'll have to check.

18:46.903 --> 18:48.004
Is it today's Globe?

18:48.024 --> 18:48.665
That's what I hear.

18:48.805 --> 18:51.108
I've got the Globe.

18:51.148 --> 18:54.733
Some guys coming tomorrow from the Globe interview me, so I'll have some fun with them.

18:54.753 --> 18:55.474
I wonder who it is.

18:55.914 --> 18:56.996
I beat them, huh?

18:57.016 --> 18:57.757
I'm here ahead of them.

18:57.777 --> 18:57.997
What?

18:58.117 --> 19:00.079
They're my competition, the Globe.

19:00.099 --> 19:00.360
The Globe?

19:01.141 --> 19:01.341
Yeah.

19:01.557 --> 19:03.359
Well, I'm the other paper, the smaller one.

19:03.479 --> 19:04.520
It goes by that review.

19:04.560 --> 19:05.882
You've got no competition.

19:06.102 --> 19:06.463
I don't.

19:07.063 --> 19:11.408
I mean, do you feel like an extinct volcano, a spent force?

19:11.528 --> 19:12.229
Do I look like one?

19:12.269 --> 19:12.569
No.

19:13.110 --> 19:14.051
I'm not.

19:14.071 --> 19:15.553
But I mean creatively, artistically.

19:16.093 --> 19:17.755
I mean, these things count too.

19:19.357 --> 19:21.359
Just because you're not doing a play or a movie.

19:21.379 --> 19:23.221
They're worth all my movies put together.

19:23.261 --> 19:24.222
That book is there.

19:24.242 --> 19:25.264
Yeah, well, I mean, that's the point.

19:25.284 --> 19:26.885
How can an extinct volcano write that book?

19:26.925 --> 19:27.586
Explain that to me.

19:27.606 --> 19:28.307
That's the point.

19:28.743 --> 19:34.529
I did an interview with this guy, everybody's, what's his name, George Amado, you ever heard of him, the Brazilian?

19:35.470 --> 19:36.672
Famous, famous writer.

19:38.173 --> 19:39.054
What's his name, Jamado?

19:39.194 --> 19:39.835
Amado.

19:39.915 --> 19:41.156
Amado, yes, my wife likes it.

19:41.176 --> 19:41.917
George Amado.

19:42.077 --> 19:43.119
My wife loves his books.

19:43.259 --> 19:45.561
Nice, nice guy.

19:47.123 --> 19:52.068
He lived in exile, he was a communist, he was thrown out of his country, he had to live in Paris.

19:53.350 --> 19:55.212
Amado, my wife loves his books.

19:55.232 --> 19:56.533
Amado, A-M-A-D-O.

19:56.553 --> 19:58.395
I know, that's the one.

19:58.645 --> 19:59.266
What's he like?

19:59.827 --> 20:00.167
Lovely.

20:00.247 --> 20:01.329
He doesn't speak any English.

20:01.369 --> 20:05.796
I interviewed him through an interpreter on tape, and it was very good.

20:05.836 --> 20:07.218
But he says he'd give everything.

20:07.238 --> 20:09.060
He's written all these books, great books.

20:09.481 --> 20:09.982
He's funny.

20:10.222 --> 20:10.763
He's funny.

20:10.803 --> 20:12.746
He's a hero in his own life.

20:12.766 --> 20:17.513
But she says, I'd trade six good books for one little poem that I could write.

20:17.573 --> 20:18.574
And I said, for one poem.

20:18.594 --> 20:20.237
I said, how long, a narrative poem?

20:20.257 --> 20:21.619
He said, no, one little poem.

20:21.699 --> 20:23.301
Six lines, he said.

20:23.361 --> 20:26.526
You ever hear about the memoirs?

20:26.877 --> 20:39.840
judge of the Supreme Court who went for a walk with somebody, and the guy asked him what he wanted most now towards the end of his life, and he said, I'd give up all my fame for one good hard-harm like I used to have.

20:40.715 --> 20:42.377
You can't tell what a guy might want.

20:42.518 --> 20:50.389
There's a wonderful cartoon in the New Yorker a couple years ago, I don't know if you remember it, but there's these two old guys sitting in leather chairs in a club.

20:50.649 --> 20:51.350
I didn't see it.

20:51.390 --> 20:54.314
And one of them says, now they tell us masturbation is good for you.

20:58.100 --> 20:59.962
I mean, you know, who needs it now, right?

21:00.683 --> 21:02.225
That's a cute story.

21:02.245 --> 21:04.709
I think I've just about covered everything.

21:05.610 --> 21:05.810
Okay.

21:06.051 --> 21:07.513
Would you kindly... Sure.

21:07.533 --> 21:07.633
Sure.

21:09.824 --> 21:11.847
Would you also inscribe it to my lovely wife?

21:12.368 --> 21:12.789
What's her name?

21:13.590 --> 21:17.136
Put this thing on my name.

21:17.196 --> 21:20.261
I don't know what he... Come downstairs, I'll give it to you.

21:20.281 --> 21:24.247
But it must be a thrill when somebody understands what you're trying to do.

21:24.367 --> 21:26.371
That's what this guy did.

21:26.391 --> 21:30.037
Whether it be a review or somebody you talk to or whatever, I guess that's important.

21:30.257 --> 21:33.021
In a book, in a movie, or a play.

21:33.061 --> 21:34.684
I don't want it anymore, now I've got this.

21:37.735 --> 21:39.778
You saved everything, huh?

21:40.799 --> 21:42.161
Those pictures with the fezzers.

21:42.682 --> 21:45.366
They look like the bottom of a drawer somewhere.

21:45.486 --> 21:47.329
See, that's a real picture right there, holding the book.

21:47.349 --> 21:47.950
You know that?

21:53.318 --> 21:53.438
Yeah.

21:53.458 --> 21:57.664
I really love this book.

21:57.684 --> 22:03.492
I bet you never worried that it would be so long that you'd never finish it, right, I hope?

22:04.273 --> 22:06.797
No, I just kept picking away.

22:12.565 --> 22:13.586
It's a great little camera.

22:14.787 --> 22:16.349
They gave me some pictures here, too.

22:19.832 --> 22:21.234
They gave me some old ones.

22:21.714 --> 22:24.236
There's one picture here of me kidding myself.

22:25.658 --> 22:26.779
Did you read the description?

22:26.819 --> 22:27.420
Remember that?

22:27.460 --> 22:28.441
There I am walking behind.

22:28.521 --> 22:30.443
I don't know what the hell I'm doing.

22:30.463 --> 22:32.164
Usually I knew what I was doing, but I didn't know.

22:32.505 --> 22:38.050
Well, these must have all been cropped by an art director who... My editor.

22:38.536 --> 22:42.787
My second editor, Bob, got me to the first one to see Kathy Hardin in the second.

22:42.807 --> 22:46.517
They've worked so hard over this.

22:46.537 --> 22:47.961
Okay, we checked everything off.

22:47.981 --> 22:48.663
I got everything.

22:48.743 --> 22:49.826
I don't think I missed anything.

22:49.846 --> 22:50.829
And this was really great.

22:51.932 --> 22:54.158
You've got a good strong handshake, my friend.

22:54.178 --> 22:54.739
Let me hear...

